UADataType.Description: Aggregates the states of an application to a simplified state model for consumption by Eagle.

Aggregates operational states of an application to a simplified state model for consumption by Eagle. Operational states might be alarm states or any other relevant application conditions that are of interest to Eagle.
Identifies the KDS internal activity mode, which determines the system sensitivity. Aggregates the rig status values of Advantage.
The sensitivity determines the kick/loss threshold values for flow comparison and the alarm level multipliers for flowback fingerprinting.

UAVariable.Description: The maximum alarm acknowledgement time specifies the maximum duration from the activation of an alarm until its acknowledgement. If the operator does not acknowledge an active alarm before the alarm acknowledgement time is up, the alarm is automatically confirmed and published.

The maximum alarm verification time specifies the maximum duration from the acknowledgement of an operator kick/loss alarm until its confirmation or discarding. If the operator does not confirm or discard an acknowledged alarm before the alarm verification time is up, the alarm is automatically confirmed and published.

The dicarded alarms counter keeps track of how many times kick/loss alarms were discarded by the users of the system. If the counter reaches a certain number, users are reminded to change the sensitivity or to revise the alarm configuration settings to receive less false alarms.

UAObject.Description: The alarm level multipliers for high sensitivity mode. Alarm level multipliers are operator-configurable values that are used to calculate the different alarm limit curves. For these calculations the standard deviation curve is multiplied with the respective multiplier values to create the different alarm limit curves.

The alarm level multipliers for low sensitivity mode. Alarm level multipliers are operator-configurable values that are used to calculate the different alarm limit curves. For these calculations the standard deviation curve is multiplied with the respective multiplier values to create the different alarm limit curves.

UAVariable.Description: At the start of a flowback event, the corridor between the level-1 kick alarm limit and the level-1 loss alarm limit is very narrow. Any alarm that is activated in this very early phase of the flowback event would therefore most likely be a false alarm. The flowback alarm grace period allows to specify a duration during which no alarm is activated, even if alarm limits are exceeded.

The flowback alarm lag time allows to specify a duration for which an alarm limit has to be exceeded by the total flowback volume curve, before an alarm is activated. This mechanism helps to prevent false alarms, because peaks of the total flowback volume curve have less effect on the alarm activation.
Determines whether flow out measurements or trip tank volumes are used as the data source for flowback fingerprinting.

When the flowback fingerprinting model was reset and is reinitialized, only the most recent previous flowback curve is considered for the new fingerprinting profile. The flowback initialization noise factor is used to calculate two temporary "previous" flowback curves based on the most recent previous flowback curve, so the model has three previous flowback curves to generate average curve.
The maximum flowback count determines the maximum number of historical/previous flowback curves that can be included into a flowback fingerprinting profile.

The maximum flowback time represents a fallback mechanism for activating a kick/loss alarm in case a very long flowback event is observed. With the maximum flowback time the operator can define after how many seconds he expects the flowback to cease. If the configured maximum flowback time is up and there is still flowback, the system activates a kick alarm, even if the total flowback volume has not exceeded any alarm limits.
Determines whether flow in is measured using a sensor or calculated based on pump strokes.
The flow out difference averaging time determines the duration that is considered for averaging the flow out difference while the system is not in kick/loss tracking mode.

The gain/loss retainment time defines the duration for which a previously accumulated total gain/loss volume will be retained after the tracking mode has changed to 0. The retainment time ensures that the gain/loss volume accumulation can be continued if the tracking mode is changing frequently.

UAObject.Description: The kick alarm limits for a specific sensitivity.
The loss alarm limits for a specific sensitivity.

UAVariable.Description: Before the kick/loss tracking threshold is exceeded, the system does not accumulate a total gain/loss volume, even if there already was a flow out difference. The concept of the total gain/loss safety margin compensates for this "missing" volume by multiplying the safety margin with the kick/loss tracking threshold and adding the result to the total gain/loss volume at the time the threshold is exceeded.

UAObject.Description: The tracking thresholds for high sensitivity and the default KDS internal rig activity mode.
The tracking thresholds for low sensitivity and the default KDS internal rig activity mode.

UAVariable.Description: The model step size is the "clock rate" or frequency of the kick/loss detection models. The step size controls how often a model/algorithm calculates ist output data per given time interval. KDS currently runs two models/algorithms: flowback fingerprinting and flow comparison, and typical output data of these models are compensated flow values, flow differences and the resulting alarm levels.

Identifies the current sensitivity of the system. The current sensitivity determines the kick/loss threshold values for flow comparison and the alarm level multipliers for flowback fingerprinting. The current sensitivity can be changed by the operator.
Identifies the KDS internal activity mode, which determines the system sensitivity. Aggregates the rig status values of Advantage.
The aggregated alarm level combining the alarm levels of the flow comparison algorithm and the flowback fingerprinting algorithm.
The alarm level that was calculated by the flowback fingerprinting algorithm.

UAObject.Description: The currently used alarm level multipliers. Alarm level multipliers are operator-configurable values that are used to calculate the different alarm limit curves. For these calculations the standard deviation curve is multiplied with the respective multiplier values to create the different alarm limit curves.

UAVariable.Description: The flowback active status indicates whether a flowback event currently recorded.

The total flowback volume indicates the total volume of mud that was gained or lost during a flowback event. It is calculated by accumulating the actual flow out volume after the mud pumps were shut down.
The alarm level that was calculated by the flow comparison algorithm.

UAObject.Description: The tracking thresholds for the current sensitivity and KDS internal rig activity mode.

UAVariable.Description: The summarized flow in is an important factor for calculating the expected flow out volume for flow comparison. It is calculated by KDS and considers the measured or calculated flow in, the trip tank volume, the diverted downlinking volume and other factors.
The actual flow out difference is calculated by subtracting the expected flow out from the measured flow out.
The averaged flow out difference is calculated by averaging the actual flow out difference over a configurable period of time.

The expected flow out volume is used to assess whether the measured flow out is off limit by calculating the flow out difference. It considers the summarized flow in and a number of compensation factors.
Estimated height of the gain/loss volume in the annulus.

The lag time that is used to calculate the expected flow out after turning off the pumps. The lag time is continuously updated by the system. The lag time is also used to determine the maximum flowback time for flowback fingerprinting.
The total gain/loss volume indicates the approximate volume of a gain or loss by accumulating the actual flow out difference while the kick/loss tracking mode is <>0.

The tracking mode indicates whether the system is currently accumulating a kick volume (+1) or a loss volume (-1). If the tracking mode is 0, the kick/loss thresholds have not been exceeded by the flow out difference and no total gain/loss volume is accumulated.
